{"title_page": "Color-Sonic", "text_new": "'''Color-Sonic''' was a type of visual [[jukebox]] developed in the United States in the 1960s.  They were the first ones to use continuous loop cartridges, which were both more durable and more easily replaced than the film reels used by their competitors, [[Cinebox]] and [[Scopitone]]. The Color-Sonic films were shot on 35&nbsp;mm, as opposed to the 16&nbsp;mm film used for Scopitone and Cinebox. Before Color-Sonic, [[Panoram]] had already pioneered the use of visual jukeboxes in America.\n\n== Company history ==\n\nIn 1966, Henry A. Schwartz filed a patent for the Color-Sonic, also known as Combi 150 (a visual jukebox) which was assigned to Color-Sonics Inc. alias National Company Inc. in New York. The Color-Sonic machines were manufactured at the facilities of the National Company Inc. in [[Melrose, Massachusetts]]. COLOR-SONICS, INC. was incorporated on May 7, 1966 in New York county with company number 198358. It is located at 122 East 42nd St. New York, New York, 10168. The National Company Inc. also used to own The National Radio Company of New York, NY.<ref name=history>[http://juke-box.dk/gert-design52-77.htm  \"Jukebox History 1952-1998\", ''Juke-Box.dk'']. Retrieved 16 April 2020</ref><ref>[http://www.qsl.net/jms/bio_rem/bhnc.html  John J. Nagle, \"A Brief History of the National Company, Inc.\", originally published by the ''Antique Wireless Association'']. Retrieved 16 April 2020</ref><ref>[http://coin-o-phone.com/history.pdf Gert J. Almind, \"The History of Coin-Operated Phonographs, 1888-1998\"]. Retrieved 16 April 2020</ref><ref name=canote>[http://mercurie.blogspot.com/2009/07/history-of-music-videos-part-three.html Terence Towles Canote, \"A History of Music Videos Part Three\", ''A Shroud of Thoughts'', July 10, 2009]. Retrieved 16 April 2020</ref>\n\n== Color Sonic music videos ==\n\nThe video films themselves were made at [[Paramount Studios]] by [[Official Films]], which was headed by [[Robert Blees]], a former producer of TV shows such as ''[[Bus Stop (TV series)|Bus Stop]]'' and ''[[Combat!]]''. [[Robert Altman]] was hired to direct the Color-Sonics films i.e. \u201cGirl Talk\u201d by [[Bobby Troup]], a short called \u201cThe Party\u201d set to the song \u201cWhipped Cream\u201d by [[Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass]], and two shorts featuring [[Lili St. Cyr]]. In addition, Color-Sonics produced a fairly sophisticated music video titled \u201c[[These Boots Are Made for Walkin']]\u201d by [[Nancy Sinatra]] which was directed by [[Robert Sidney (choreographer)|Robert Sidney]].<ref name=canote/><ref>[http://nancysinatra.com/blog/2015/08/nancys-color-sonics-films-part-two-from-the-tough-and-wise-boots-to-the-gentle-and-sexy-shadow-of-your-smile/ \"Nancy\u2019s Color-Sonics Films, Part Two: From the Tough and Wise \u201cBoots\u201d to the Gentle and Sexy \u201cShadow of Your Smile\u201d\", ''NancySinatra.com'', August 10, 2015]. Retrieved 16 April 2020</ref><ref>http://mariagrillo.blogspot.com/2010/09/history-of-music-videos-scopitones.html Maria Grillo, \"History of Music Videos - Scopitones\", ''Maria Grillo's Blog'', 24 September 2010]. Retrieved 16 April 2020</ref><ref name=variety>[https://variety.com/2008/scene/markets-festivals/dancer-robert-sidney-dies-at-98-1117983483/ \"Dancer Robert Sidney dies at 98: Choreographed 'Where the Boys Are,' 'Dolls'\", ''Variety'', April 3, 2008]. Retrieved 16 April 2010</ref>\n\nSome other music videos featured on Color-Sonic included;\n\n# Fran Jeffries \u201cNo Moon At All\u201d\n# Lynn Elliot \u201cBaby Face\u201d\n# Jaye P. Morgan \u201cWill He Like Me\u201d\n# Nancy Sinatra \u201cThe Shadow of Your Smile\u201d (dir. by Robert Sidney)\n# Lainie Kazan \u201cBlues in the Night\u201d\n# Nancy Sinatra \u201cThese Boots Are Made For Walking\u201d (dir. by Robert Sidney)\n# Herb Alpert & The Tijuana Brass \u201cWhipped Cream\u201d\n# Frankie Randall \u201cThe Rules of the Road\u201d (dir. by Bob Baker)\n# Janice Harper \u201cLove Is A Dangerous Thing\u201d\n# Janice Harper \u201cThe Thrill Is Gone\u201d\n# Boots Randolph \u201cCharlie Brown\u201d\n# Mary Jane Mangler \u201cShe\u2019s Not There\u201d\n# Herb Alpert & The Tijuana Brass \u201cSwinger From Seville\u201d\n# Frankie Randall \u201cMore\u201d (dir. by Bob Baker)\n# Lili St. Cyr \u201cSpeak Low\u201d (dir. by Robert Altman)\n# Mary Wells \u201cAll My Lovin'\u201d\n# Julie London \u201cWatermelon Man\u201d\n# \u201cIn Crowd\u201d aka \u201cThe Party\u201d aka Herb Alpert & The Tijuana Brass \u201cBittersweet Samba\u201d (dir. by Robert Altman)\n# Karen Jensen \u201cI\u2019m An Old Cowhand\u201d\n# Ray Anthony Show \u201cWhat\u2019d I Say\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cSeventh Veil\u201d\n# Bobby Troup \u201cGirl Talk\u201d (dir. by Robert Altman)\n# Fran Jeffries \u201cSqueeze Me\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cYou Are My Sunshine\u201d\n# Fran Jeffries \u201cShow Me The Way To Go Home\u201d\n# Vi Velasco \u201cBye Bye Black Bird\u201d\n# Unknown Artist \u201cAgent 006\u201d\n# Kitty Oliver \u201cKansas City\u201d\n# Natali Moore \u201cBig Bad Bill\u201d\n# The Eggheads \u201cThis Little Lite of Mine\u201d\n# The Eggheads \u201cGreenback Dollar\u201d\n# Tina Robbins \u201cGlory of Love\u201d\n# Lonnie Sattin \u201cSweetheart\u201d\n# Colorama Dancers \u201cBeach Party\u201d\n# Dawn Holly \u201cCoquette\u201d\n# Lili St. Cyr \u201cEbb Tide\u201d (dir. by Robert Altman)\n# Unknown artist \u201cLady In Red\u201d\n# Shawn Elliott \u201cShame and Scandal in the Family\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cSeven-Eleven Go-Go\u201d\n# Mary Pastor \u201cWinning Pair\u201d\n# Fran Jeffries \u201cShow Me the Way To Go Home\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cAlley Cat\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cThe Girl From Ipanema\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cSt. Louis Blues\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cSea Witch\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cYou\u2019re Driving Me Crazy\u201d\n# Unknown Artist \u201cEvery Little Movement\u201d\n# Johnny B. Great \u201cIf I Had A Hammer\u201d\n# Fay Craig \u201cMirage\u201d\n# Wayne Gibson \u201cI Like It\u201d\n# Fay Craig \u201cBongo Baby\u201d\n# Bobby Breen \u201cUp on the Roof\u201d\n# Brothers Two Trio \u201cChickie\u201d\n# Andy Cavell & The Boscoe Holder Dancers \u201cSpeedy Gonzalez\u201d\n# The Eggheads \u201cSwing Low, Sweet Chariot\u201d\n# Shane Fenton \u201cI Ain\u2019t Got Nobody\u201d\n# Fran Jeffries \u201cAin\u2019t Misbehavin'\u201d\n# Lainie Kazan \u201cI Cried For You\u201d\n# Joi Lansing \u201cAll of Me\u201d\n# Tommy Leonetti \u201cThe Way You Look Tonight\u201d\n# Terry Ross \u201cMy Baby Just Cares For Me\u201d\n# Frank Sinatra Jr. \u201cLove For Sale\u201d\n# Ozel Turkbas \u201cBedevilled Belly Dancer\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cBesame Mucho\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cBikini Beach\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cCobra Dance\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cDerelict\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cDown By The Riverside\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cGoldie\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cHey Look Me Over\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cThe Limbo\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cMack the Knife\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cNight Train\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cSan Francisco\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cSugar Daddy\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cWhat a Difference a Day Makes\u201d\n# Mary Wells \u201cHe Loves You\u201d\n# Connie Francis\n# Leslie Uggams.\n# Bobby Troup \u201cGirl Talk\u201d (dir. by Robert Altman)\n# Karen Jensen \u201cI\u2019m An Old Cowhand\u201d\n# Unknown artist \u201cEvery Little Movement\u201d\n# Ray Anthony Show\n# Julie London \u201cDaddy\u201d\n# Boots Randolph \u201cCharlie Brown\u201d\n# Fran Jeffries \u201cAin\u2019t Misbehavin'\u201d\n# Lili St. Cyr \u201cSpeak Low\u201d (dir. by Robert Altman)\n# Nai Bonet \u201cJelly Belly\u201d\n# Lili St. Cyr \u201cEbb Tide\u201d (dir. by Robert Altman)\n# \u201cIn Crowd\u201d aka \u201cThe Party\u201d aka Herb Alpert & The Tijuana Brass \u201cBittersweet Samba\u201d (dir. by Robert Altman)\n# Nancy Sinatra \u