{"title_page": "Microfluidics", "text_new": "{{short description|Interdisciplinary science}}\n'''Microfluidics''' refers to the behaviour, precise control, and manipulation of [[fluids]] that are geometrically constrained to a small scale (typically sub-millimeter) at which capillary penetration governs mass transport. It is a multidisciplinary field that involves [[engineering]], [[physics]], [[chemistry]], [[biochemistry]], [[nanotechnology]], and [[biotechnology]]. It has practical applications in the design of systems that process low volumes of fluids to achieve [[multiplexing]], automation, and [[high-throughput screening]]. Microfluidics emerged in the beginning of the 1980s and is used in the development of [[inkjet]] printheads, [[DNA chip]]s, [[lab-on-a-chip]] technology, micro-propulsion, and micro-thermal technologies.\n\nTypically, micro means one of the following features:\n\n* Small volumes (\u03bcL, nL, pL, fL)\n* Small size\n* Low energy consumption\n* Microdomain effects\n\nTypically microfluidic systems transport, mix, separate, or otherwise process fluids. Various applications rely on passive fluid control using [[capillary force]]s, in the form of capillary flow modifying elements, akin to flow resistors and flow accelerators. In some applications, external actuation means are additionally used for a directed transport of the media. Examples are rotary drives applying centrifugal forces for the fluid transport on the passive chips. '''Active microfluidics''' refers to the defined manipulation of the working fluid by active (micro) components such as [[micropump]]s or [[microvalve]]s. Micropumps supply fluids in a continuous manner or are used for dosing. Microvalves determine the flow direction or the mode of movement of pumped liquids. Often, processes normally carried out in a lab are miniaturised on a single chip, which enhances efficiency and mobility, and reduces sample and reagent volumes.\n\n==Microscale behaviour of fluids==\n[[File:Microfluidics.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Silicone rubber and glass microfluidic devices. Top: a photograph of the devices. Bottom: [[Phase contrast]] [[micrograph]]s of a serpentine channel ~15 [[\u03bcm]] wide.]]\nThe behaviour of fluids at the microscale can differ from \"macrofluidic\" behaviour in that factors such as [[surface tension]], energy dissipation, and fluidic resistance start to dominate the system. Microfluidics studies how these behaviours change, and how they can be worked around, or exploited for new uses.<ref>S.C.Terry, J.H.Jerman and J.B.Angell:A Gas Chromatographic Air Analyzer Fabricated on a Silicon Wafer, IEEE Trans.Electron Devices, ED-26,12(1979)1880-1886.</ref><ref name=Kirby>{{cite book | author=Kirby, B.J. | title=Micro- and Nanoscale Fluid Mechanics: Transport in Microfluidic Devices | url=http://www.kirbyresearch.com/textbook | year=2010 | publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]}}</ref><ref name=Karniadakis>{{cite book | author1=Karniadakis, G.M. | author2=Beskok, A. | author3=Aluru, N. | title=Microflows and Nanoflows | year=2005 | publisher =[[Springer Verlag]] }}</ref><ref name=Bruus>{{cite book | author=Bruus, H. | title=Theoretical Microfluidics | year=2007 | publisher =[[Oxford University Press]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Principles of Microfluidics|last=Shkolnikov|first=V|year=2019|isbn=978-1790217281|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nAt small scales (channel size of around 100 [[nanometers]] to 500 [[micrometers]]) some interesting and sometimes unintuitive properties appear. In particular, the [[Reynolds number]] (which compares the effect of the momentum of a fluid to the effect of [[viscosity]]) can become very low. A key consequence is co-flowing fluids do not necessarily mix in the traditional sense, as flow becomes [[laminar flow|laminar]] rather than [[turbulent flow|turbulent]]; molecular transport between them must often be through [[diffusion]].<ref name=Tabeling>{{cite book | author=Tabeling, P. | title=Introduction to Microfluidics | url=https://archive.org/details/introductiontomi0000tabe | url-access=registration | year=2005 | publisher =[[Oxford University Press]] }}</ref>\n\nHigh specificity of chemical and physical properties (concentration, pH, temperature, shear force, etc.) can also be ensured resulting in more uniform reaction conditions and higher grade products in single and multi-step reactions.<ref name=\"microreactors\">{{cite journal | last1 = Chokkalingam | first1 = V. | last2 = Weidenhof | first2 = B. | last3 = Kraemer | first3 = M. | last4 = Maier | first4 = W. F. | last5 = Herminghaus | first5 = S. | last6 = Seemann | first6 = R. | year = 2010 | title = Optimized droplet-based microfluidics scheme for sol\u2013gel reactions | journal = Lab Chip | volume =  10| issue = 13| pages = 1700\u20135 | doi = 10.1039/b926976b | pmid = 20405061 }}</ref><ref name=\"microfluidic reactions\">{{cite journal | last1 = Shestopalov | first1 = J | last2 = Tice | first2 = J. D. | last3 = Ismagilov | first3 = R. F. | year = 2004 | title = Multi-step synthesis of nanoparticles performed on millisecond time scale in a microfluidic droplet-based system | journal = Lab Chip | volume = 4 | issue = 4| pages = 316\u2013321 | doi = 10.1039/b403378g | pmid = 15269797 | url = https://authors.library.caltech.edu/40869/1/Ismagilov_LOC_2004_4_316_Shestopalov_Mulitstep_synthesis_nanoparticles_ms_timescale_ufl_droplet_system.pdf}}<!--https://authors.library.caltech.edu/40869/1/Ismagilov_LOC_2004_4_316_Shestopalov_Mulitstep_synthesis_nanoparticles_ms_timescale_ufl_droplet_system.pdf }}--></ref>\n\n==Key application areas==\n\nMicrofluidic structures include micropneumatic systems, i.e. microsystems for the handling of off-chip fluids (liquid pumps, gas valves, etc.), and microfluidic structures for the on-chip handling of nanoliter (nl) and picoliter (pl) volumes.<ref name=Nguyen>{{cite book | author1=Nguyen, N.T. | author2=Wereley, S. | title=Fundamentals and Applications of Microfluidics | year=2006 | publisher =[[Artech House]] }}</ref>  To date, the most successful commercial application of microfluidics is the [[Inkjet printer|inkjet printhead]].<ref name=\"microfluidics1\">{{cite journal | last1 = Andrew | year = 2006 | title = Control and detection of chemical reactions in microfluidic systems | journal = Nature | volume = 442 | issue = 7101| pages = 394\u2013402 | doi = 10.1038/nature05062 | pmid = 16871207 |bibcode = 2006Natur.442..394D }}</ref> <!-- and other industrially relevant materials (e.g., polymer particles).<ref name=\"modular microfluidics\">{{cite journal | last1 = Li | first1 = Wei | last2 = Greener | first2 = Jesse | last3 = Voicu | first3 = Dan | last4 = Kumacheva | first4 = Eugenia | year = 2009 | title = Multiple modular microfluidic (M3) reactors for the synthesis of polymer particles | url = http://www.rsc.org/Publishing/Journals/LC/article.asp?doi=b906626h | journal = Lab Chip | volume = 9 | issue = | pages = 2715\u20132721 | doi = 10.1039/b906626h }}</ref> -->Additionally, microfluidic manufacturing advances mean that makers can produce the devices in low-cost plastics<ref name=\"researchgate.net\">{{cite journal|last1=Pawell|first1=Ryan S.|last2=Inglis|first2=David W.|last3=Barber|first3=Tracie J.|last4=Taylor|first4=Robert A.|year=2013|title=Manufacturing and wetting low-cost microfluidic cell separation devices|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/256487052|journal=Biomicrofluidics|volume=7|issue=5|pages=056501|doi=10.1063/1.4821315|pmc=3785532|pmid=24404077}}</ref> and automatically verify part quality.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1007/s10404-014-1464-1|title = Automating microfluidic part verification|journal = Microfluidics and Nanofluidics|volume = 18|issue = 4|pages = 657\u2013665|year = 2015|last1 = Pawell|first1 = Ryan S.|last2 = Taylor|first2 = Robert A.|last3 = Morris|first3 = Kevin V.|last4 = Barber|first4 = Tracie J.}}</ref> \n\nAdvances in microfluidics technology are revolutionizing [[molecular biology]] procedures for enzymatic analysis (e.g.,  [[glucose]] and [[lactic acid|lactate]] [[assay]]s), [[DNA]] analysis (e.g., [[polymerase chain reaction]] and high-throughput [[sequencing]]), [[proteomics]], and in chemical synthesis.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Morin|first=Stephen A.|last2=Konda|first2=Abhiteja|date=2017-06-22|title=Flow-directed synthesis of spatially variant arrays of branched zinc oxide mesostructures|journal=Nanoscale|language=en|volume=9|issue=24|pages=8393\u20138400|doi=10.1039/C7NR02655B|pmid=28604901|issn=2040-3372}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=Jayce J.|last2=Nicaise|first2=Samuel M.|last3=Berggren|first3=Karl K.|last4=Grade\u010dak|first4=Silvija|date=2016-01-13|title=Dimensional Tailoring of Hydrothermally Grown Zinc Oxide Nanowire Arrays|journal=Nano Letters|volume=16|issue=1|pages=753\u2013759|doi=10.1021/acs.nanolett.5b04625|pmid=26708095|issn=1530-6984|bibcode=2016NanoL..16..753C}}</ref> The basic idea of microfluidic biochips is to integrate [[assay]] operations such as detection, as well as sample pre-treatment and sample preparation on one chip.<ref name= Herold1>{{cite book |author1= Herold, KE |editor=Rasooly, A | year=2009 |title=Lab-on-a-Chip Technology: Fabrication and Microfluidics | publisher=Caister Academic Press | isbn= 978-1-904455-46-2}}</ref><ref name= Herold2>{{cite book |author1= Herold, KE |editor=Rasooly, A | year=2009 |title=Lab-on-a-Chip Technology: Biomolecular Separation and Analysis | publisher=Caister Academic Press | isbn= 978-1-904455-47-9}}</ref>\n\nAn emerging application area for biochips is [[clinical pathology]], especially the immediate [[point-of-care]] diagnosis of [[diseases]].<ref name=\"Barrett Microfluidics-Based 2017\">{{cite journal|author1=Michael P. Barrett |author2=Jonathan M. Cooper |author3=Cl\u00e9ment Regnault |author4=Stefan H. Holm |author5=Jason P. Beech |author6= Jonas O. Tegenfeldt |author7=Axel Hochstetter |date= 5 October 2017 |title=Microfluidics-Based Approaches to the Isolation of African Trypanosomes|journal= Pathogens |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=47 |doi=10.3390/pathogens6040047  | pmid=28981471|pmc=5750571 }}</ref> In addition, microfluidics-based devices, capable of continuous sampling and real-time testing of air/water samples for biochemical [[toxins]] and other dangerous [[pathogens]], can serve as an always-on [[smoke alarm|\"bio-smoke alarm\"]] for early warning.\n\nMicrofluidic technology has led to the creation of powerful tools for biologists to control the complete cellular environment, leading to new questions and discoveries. Many diverse advantages of this technology for microbiology are listed below:\n* General single cell studies including growth <ref name=\"pmid20537537\"/><ref name=\"pubs.rsc.org\"/>\n* Cellular aging: microfluidic devices such as the \"mother machine\" allow tracking of thousands of individual cells for many generations until they die.<ref name=\"pmid20537537\">{{Cite journal | pmid = 20537537 | year = 2010 | last1 = Wang| first1 = P | title = Robust growth of Escherichia coli | journal = Current Biology| volume = 20| issue = 12| pages = 1099\u20131103 | last2 = Robert| first2 = L| last3 = Dang| first3 = WL| last4 = Taddei| first4 = F| last5 = Wright| first5 = A| last6 = Jun| first6 = S | doi = 10.1016/j.cub.2010.04.045 | pmc =2902570 }}</ref>\n* Microenvironmental control: ranging from mechanical environment <ref>{{cite journal |author1=Amir Manbachi |author2=Shamit Shrivastava |author3=Margherita Cioffi |author4=Bong Geun Chung |author5=Matteo Moretti |author6=Utkan Demirci |author7=Marjo Yliperttula |author8=Ali Khademhosseini |title=Microcirculation within grooved substrates regulates cell positioning and cell docking inside microfluidic channels  |journal= Lab Chip |volume=8 |issue= 5|pages= 747\u2013754 |year=2008 |pmid=18432345 |doi= 10.1039/B718212K |pmc=2668874}}</ref> to chemical environment <ref>{{cite journal |author=1 Marjo Yliperttulaa | author2=Bong Geun Chunga | author3=Akshay Navaladia | author4=Amir Manbachi | author5=Arto Urtt|title=High-throughput screening of cell responses to biomaterials |journal= European Journal of Pharmaceutical Sciences |volume=35 |issue=3 |pages= 151\u2013160  |date=October 2008 |pmid=18586092 |doi= 10.1016/j.ejps.2008.04.012 }}</ref> <ref>{{cite journal |author1= Daniel F. Gilbert | author2=Sepideh Abolpour Mofrad | author3=Oliver Friedrich | author4=Joachim Wiest|title=Proliferation characteristics of cells cultured under periodic versus static conditions |journal= Cytotechnology |volume=71 |issue=1 |pages= 443\u2013452  |date=February 2019 |pmid=30515656 |pmc=6368509 |doi= 10.1007/s10616-018-0263-z }}</ref>\n* Precise spatiotemporal concentration gradients by incorporating multiple chemical inputs to a single device <ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Chung BG, Manbachi A, Saadi W, Lin F, Jeon NL, Khademhosseini A |title=A gradient-generating microfluidic device for cell biology. |journal= J Vis Exp |volume=7 |issue= 7|page= 271 |year=2007 |pmid=18989442  |doi= 10.3791/271|pmc=2565846}}</ref>\n* Force measurements of adherent cells or confined chromosomes: objects trapped in a microfluidic device can be directly manipulated using [[optical tweezers]] or other force-generating methods <ref name=\"pmid22984156\">{{Cite journal | pmid = 22984156 | year = 2012 | last1 = Pelletier| first1 = J | title = Physical manipulation of the Escherichia coli chromosome reveals its soft nature | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 109| issue = 40| pages = E2649\u2013E2656 | last2 = Halvorsen| first2 = K| last3 = Ha| first3 = BY| last4 = Paparcone| first4 = R| last5 = Sandler| first5 = S| last6 = Woldringh| first6 = CL| last7 = Wong| first7 = WP| last8 = Jun| first8 = S | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1208689109 | pmc =3479577 | bibcode = 2012PNAS..109E2649P}}</ref>\n* Confining cells and exerting controlled forces by coupling with external force-generation methods such as [[Stokes flow]], [[optical tweezer]], or controlled deformation of the PDMS ([[Polydimethylsiloxane]]) device <ref name=\"pmid22984156\" /><ref name=\"pmid24711421\">{{Cite journal | pmid = 24711421 | year = 2014 | last1 = Amir| first1 = A | title = Bending forces plastically deform growing bacterial cell walls | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 111| issue = 16| pages = 5778\u20135783 | last2 = Babaeipour| first2 = F| last3 = McIntosh| first3 = D| last4 = Nelson| first4 = D| last5 = Jun| first5 = S | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1317497111 | pmc =4000856 | arxiv = 1305.5843| bibcode = 2014PNAS..111.5778A}}</ref><ref name=\"jw\">{{Cite journal | doi=10.1039/B917719A| pmid=20221568| title=3-dimensional electrode patterning within a microfluidic channel using metal ion implantation| journal=Lab on a Chip| volume=10| issue=6| pages=783\u20138| year=2010| last1=Choi| first1=Jae-Woo| last2=Rosset| first2=Samuel| last3=Niklaus| first3=Muhamed| last4=Adleman| first4=James R.| last5=Shea| first5=Herbert| last6=Psaltis| first6=Demetri| url=https://authors.library.caltech.edu/17871/1/Choi2010p7366Lab_on_a_Chip.pdf}}</ref>\n* Electric field integration <ref name=\"jw\" />\n* Plant on a chip and plant tissue culture <ref>{{cite journal |author1=AK Yetisen |author2=L Jiang |author3=J R Cooper |author4=Y Qin |author5=R Palanivelu |author6=Y Zohar |title=A microsystem-based assay for studying pollen tube guidance in plant reproduction. |journal= J. Micromech. Microeng. |volume=25 |issue= 5|pages= 054018|date=May 2011 |pmid=  |doi= 10.1088/0960-1317/21/5/054018|bibcode=2011JMiMi..21e4018Y |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/29e1fab1cb05a5763e95baea2f754cad3cf9e03a }}</ref>\n* Antibiotic resistance: microfluidic devices can be used as heterogeneous environments for microorganisms. In a heterogeneous environment, it is easier for a microorganism to evolve. This can be useful for testing the acceleration of evolution of a microorganism / for testing the development of antibiotic resistance.\n\nSome of these areas are further elaborated in the sections below.\n\n=== Open microfluidics ===\nIn [[open microfluidics]], at least one boundary of the system is removed, exposing the fluid to air or another interface (i.e. liquid).<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Berthier|first=Jean|last2=Brakke|first2=Kenneth A.|last3=Berthier|first3=Erwin|date=2016-08-01|title=Open Microfluidics|doi=10.1002/9781118720936|isbn=9781118720936}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pfohl|first=Thomas|last2=Mugele|first2=Frieder|last3=Seemann|first3=Ralf|last4=Herminghaus|first4=Stephan|date=2003-12-08|title=Trends in Microfluidics with Complex Fluids|journal=ChemPhysChem|volume=4|issue=12|pages=1291\u20131298|doi=10.1002/cphc.200300847|pmid=14714376|issn=1439-4235}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Kaigala|first=Govind V.|last2=Lovchik|first2=Robert D.|last3=Delamarche|first3=Emmanuel|date=2012-10-30|title=Microfluidics in the \"Open Space\" for Performing Localized Chemistry on Biological Interfaces|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|volume=51|issue=45|pages=11224\u201311240|doi=10.1002/anie.201201798|pmid=23111955|issn=1433-7851}}</ref> Advantages of open microfluidics include accessibility to the flowing liquid for intervention, larger liquid-gas surface area, and minimized bubble formation.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Li|first=C.|last2=Boban|first2=M.|last3=Tuteja|first3=A.|date=2017|title=Open-channel, water-in-oil emulsification in paper-based microfluidic devices|journal=Lab on a Chip|volume=17|issue=8|pages=1436\u20131441|doi=10.1039/c7lc00114b|pmid=28322402|issn=1473-0197|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/75ea2dc3e175485be7b02ef093ba2a56db9eb939}}</ref>  Another advantage of open microfluidics is the ability to integrate open systems with surface-tension driven fluid flow, which eliminates the need for external pumping methods such as peristaltic or syringe pumps.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Casavant|first=B. P.|last2=Berthier|first2=E.|last3=Theberge|first3=A. B.|last4=Berthier|first4=J.|last5=Montanez-Sauri|first5=S. I.|last6=Bischel|first6=L. L.|last7=Brakke|first7=K.|last8=Hedman|first8=C. J.|last9=Bushman|first9=W.|date=2013-05-31|title=Suspended microfluidics|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=110|issue=25|pages=10111\u201310116|doi=10.1073/pnas.1302566110|pmid=23729815|issn=0027-8424|bibcode=2013PNAS..11010111C|pmc=3690848}}</ref> Open microfluidic devices are also easy and inexpensive to fabricate by milling, thermoforming, and hot embossing.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guckenberger|first=David J.|last2=de Groot|first2=Theodorus E.|last3=Wan|first3=Alwin M. D.|last4=Beebe|first4=David J.|last5=Young|first5=Edmond W. K.|date=2015|title=Micromilling: a method for ultra-rapid prototyping of plastic microfluidic devices|journal=Lab on a Chip|volume=15|issue=11|pages=2364\u20132378|doi=10.1039/c5lc00234f|pmid=25906246|issn=1473-0197|pmc=4439323}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Truckenm$uuml$ller|first=R|last2=Rummler|first2=Z|last3=Schaller|first3=Th|last4=Schomburg|first4=W K|date=2002-06-13|title=Low-cost thermoforming of micro fluidic analysis chips|journal=Journal of Micromechanics and Microengineering|volume=12|issue=4|pages=375\u2013379|doi=10.1088/0960-1317/12/4/304|issn=0960-1317|bibcode=2002JMiMi..12..375T}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jeon|first=Jessie S.|last2=Chung|first2=Seok|last3=Kamm|first3=Roger D.|last4=Charest|first4=Joseph L.|date=2010-11-27|title=Hot embossing for fabrication of a microfluidic 3D cell culture platform|journal=Biomedical Microdevices|volume=13|issue=2|pages=325\u2013333|doi=10.1007/s10544-010-9496-0|pmid=21113663|pmc=3117225|issn=1387-2176}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Young|first=Edmond W. K.|last2=Berthier|first2=Erwin|last3=Guckenberger|first3=David J.|last4=Sackmann|first4=Eric|last5=Lamers|first5=Casey|last6=Meyvantsson|first6=Ivar|last7=Huttenlocher|first7=Anna|last8=Beebe|first8=David J.|date=2011-02-15|title=Rapid Prototyping of Arrayed Microfluidic Systems in Polystyrene for Cell-Based Assays|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=83|issue=4|pages=1408\u20131417|doi=10.1021/ac102897h|pmid=21261280|pmc=3052265|issn=0003-2700}}</ref> In addition, open microfluidics eliminates the need to glue or bond a cover for devices, which could be detrimental to capillary flows. Examples of open microfluidics include open-channel microfluidics, rail-based microfluidics, [[Paper-based microfluidics|paper-based]], and thread-based microfluidics.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bouaidat|first=Salim|last2=Hansen|first2=Ole|last3=Bruus|first3=Henrik|last4=Berendsen|first4=Christian|last5=Bau-Madsen|first5=Niels Kristian|last6=Thomsen|first6=Peter|last7=Wolff|first7=Anders|last8=Jonsmann|first8=Jacques|date=2005|title=Surface-directed capillary system; theory, experiments and applications|journal=Lab on a Chip|volume=5|issue=8|pages=827\u201336|doi=10.1039/b502207j|pmid=16027933|issn=1473-0197|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5ef7c241b4a01dc438d45b38aa5793e2401b3961}}</ref>  Disadvantages to open systems include susceptibility to evaporation,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kachel|first=Sibylle|last2=Zhou|first2=Ying|last3=Scharfer|first3=Philip|last4=Vran\u010di\u0107|first4=Christian|last5=Petrich|first5=Wolfgang|last6=Schabel|first6=Wilhelm|date=2014|title=Evaporation from open microchannel grooves|journal=Lab Chip|volume=14|issue=4|pages=771\u2013778|doi=10.1039/c3lc50892g|pmid=24345870|issn=1473-0197}}</ref> contamination,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Higashi|first=Kazuhiko|last2=Ogawa|first2=Miho|last3=Fujimoto|first3=Kazuma|last4=Onoe|first4=Hiroaki|last5=Miki|first5=Norihisa|date=2017-06-03|title=Hollow Hydrogel Microfiber Encapsulating Microorganisms for Mass-Cultivation in Open Systems|journal=Micromachines|volume=8|issue=6|pages=176|doi=10.3390/mi8060176|issn=2072-666X|pmc=6190135}}</ref> and limited flow rate.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Continuous-flow microfluidics===\n\nContinuous flow microfluidics rely on the control of a steady state [[steady flow|liquid flow]] through narrow channels or porous media predominantly by accelerating or hindering fluid flow in capillary elements.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Morin|first=Stephen A.|last2=Konda|first2=Abhiteja|date=2017-06-22|title=Flow-directed synthesis of spatially variant arrays of branched zinc oxide mesostructures|journal=Nanoscale|language=en|volume=9|issue=24|pages=8393\u20138400|doi=10.1039/C7NR02655B|pmid=28604901|issn=2040-3372}}</ref> In paper based microfluidics, capillary elements can be achieved through the simple variation of section geometry. In general, the actuation of [[steady flow|liquid flow]] is implemented either by external [[pressure]] sources, external mechanical [[pump]]s, integrated mechanical [[micropump]]s, or by combinations of capillary forces and [[Electrohydrodynamics|electrokinetic]] mechanisms.<ref name=Chang>{{cite book | author1=Chang, H.C. | author2=Yeo, Leslie | title=Electrokinetically Driven Microfluidics and Nanofluidics | year=2009 | publisher =[[Cambridge University Press]] }}</ref><ref>[http://www.cytonix.com/fluid%20transistor.html fluid transistor<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708215908/http://www.cytonix.com/fluid%20transistor.html |date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref>  Continuous-flow microfluidic operation is the mainstream approach because it is easy to implement and less sensitive to protein fouling problems. Continuous-flow devices are adequate for many well-defined and simple biochemical applications, and for certain tasks such as chemical separation, but they are less suitable for tasks requiring a high degree of flexibility or fluid manipulations. These closed-channel systems are inherently difficult to integrate and scale because the parameters that govern flow field vary along the flow path making the fluid flow at any one location dependent on the properties of the entire system. Permanently etched microstructures also lead to limited reconfigurability and poor fault tolerance capability. Computer-aided design automation approaches for continuous-flow microfluidics have been proposed in recent years to alleviate the design effort and to solve the scalability problems.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1109/TCAD.2017.2760628|title = Columba 2.0: A Co-Layout Synthesis Tool for Continuous-Flow Microfluidic Biochips|year = 2018|last1 = Tseng|first1 = Tsun-Ming|last2 = Li|first2 = Mengchu|last3 = Freitas|first3 = Daniel Nestor|last4 = McAuley|first4 = Travis|last5 = Li|first5 = Bing|last6 = Ho|first6 = Tsung-Yi|last7 = Araci|first7 = Ismail Emre|last8 = Schlichtmann|first8 = Ulf|journal = IEEE Transactions on Computer-Aided Design of Integrated Circuits and Systems|volume = 37|issue = 8|pages = 1588\u20131601}}</ref>\n\nProcess monitoring capabilities in continuous-flow systems can be achieved with highly sensitive microfluidic flow sensors based on [[Microelectromechanical systems|MEMS]] technology, which offers resolutions down to the nanoliter range.\n\n===Droplet-based microfluidics===\n\n[[File: Gas4psi LONDs26uLmin-1 50kfps x10lens.webm|thumb|High frame rate video showing microbubble pinch-off formation in a flow-focusing microfluidic device <ref name=DOI153>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.5518/153|year = 2018|last1 = Churchman|first1 = Adam H.|title = Data associated with 'Combined flow-focus and self-assembly routes for the formation of lipid stabilized oil-shelled microbubbles'|publisher = University of Leeds}}</ref>]]\n\n{{Main|Droplet-based microfluidics}}\nDroplet-based microfluidics is a subcategory of microfluidics in contrast with continuous microfluidics; droplet-based microfluidics manipulates discrete volumes of fluids in immiscible phases with low Reynolds number and laminar flow regimes. Interest in droplet-based microfluidics systems has been growing substantially in past decades. Microdroplets allow for handling miniature volumes (\u03bcl to fl) of fluids conveniently, provide better mixing, encapsulation, sorting, and sensing, and suit high throughput experiments.<ref name=\"pubs.rsc.org\">{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1039/C3LC50945A|pmid = 24185478|title = Probing cellular heterogeneity in cytokine-secreting immune cells using droplet-based microfluidics|journal = Lab on a Chip|volume = 13|issue = 24|pages = 4740\u20134|year = 2013|last1 = Chokkalingam|first1 = Venkatachalam|last2 = Tel|first2 = Jurjen|last3 = Wimmers|first3 = Florian|last4 = Liu|first4 = Xin|last5 = Semenov|first5 = Sergey|last6 = Thiele|first6 = Julian|last7 = Figdor|first7 = Carl G.|last8 = Huck|first8 = Wilhelm T. S.|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/af8bc9bfcbda303e7cffc8f696d7043b265e0a15}}</ref> Exploiting the benefits of droplet-based microfluidics efficiently requires a deep understanding of droplet generation <ref name=\"droplet microfluidics\" /> to perform various logical operations<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|year=2008|title=Droplet microfluidics|journal=Lab on a Chip|volume=8|pages=198\u2013220|doi=10.1039/B715524G|pmid=18231657|author1=Teh, Shia-Yen | author2=Lin, Robert | author3=Hung, Lung-Hsin  | author4=Lee, Abraham P|number=2|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/8b269d6b41df2951dee25469bf389e4438666140}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Prakash|first=Manu|last2=Gershenfeld|first2=Neil|date=2007-02-09|title=Microfluidic Bubble Logic|journal=Science|language=en|volume=315|issue=5813|pages=832\u2013835|doi=10.1126/science.1136907|issn=0036-8075|pmid=17289994|bibcode=2007Sci...315..832P|citeseerx=10.1.1.673.2864}}</ref> such as droplet motion, droplet sorting, droplet merging, and droplet breakup.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Samie|first=Milad|author2=Salari, Shafii|title=Breakup of microdroplets in asymmetric T junctions|journal=Physical Review E|date=May 2013|volume=87|issue=5|pages=053003|doi=10.1103/PhysRevE.87.053003|pmid=23767616|bibcode = 2013PhRvE..87e3003S }}</ref>\n\n===Digital microfluidics===\n\nAlternatives to the above closed-channel continuous-flow systems include novel open structures, where discrete, independently controllable droplets\nare manipulated on a substrate using [[electrowetting]]. Following the analogy of digital microelectronics, this approach is referred to as [[digital microfluidics]]. Le Pesant et al. pioneered the use of electrocapillary forces to move droplets on a digital track.<ref>Le Pesant et al., Electrodes for a device operating by electrically controlled fluid displacement, U.S. Pat. No. 4,569,575, Feb. 11, 1986.</ref> The \"fluid transistor\" pioneered by Cytonix<ref>[https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/piSearch.do;jsessionid=D05E82394F781CBA17DB0C5AC8E3C0B8?SearchType=piSearch&page=1&QueryText=&PIFirstName=james&PILastName=brown&PIInstitution=cytonix&PIState=MD&PIZip=&PICountry=US&RestrictExpired=on&Search=Search#results NSF Award Search: Advanced Search Results<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> also played a role. The technology was subsequently commercialised by Duke University. By using discrete unit-volume droplets,<ref name=\"droplet microfluidics\">{{cite journal | last1 = Chokkalingam | first1 = V. | last2 = Herminghaus | first2 = S. | last3 = Seemann | first3 = R. | year = 2008 | title = Self-synchronizing Pairwise Production of Monodisperse Droplets by Microfluidic Step Emulsification | url = http://apl.aip.org/applab/v93/i25/p254101_s1 | journal = Applied Physics Letters | volume = 93 | issue =  25| page = 254101 | doi = 10.1063/1.3050461 | bibcode = 2008ApPhL..93y4101C | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.is/20130113004540/http://apl.aip.org/applab/v93/i25/p254101_s1 | archivedate = 2013-01-13 }}</ref>  a microfluidic function can be reduced to a set of repeated basic operations, i.e., moving one unit of fluid over one unit of distance. This \"digitisation\" method facilitates the use of a hierarchical and cell-based approach for microfluidic biochip design. Therefore, digital microfluidics offers a flexible and scalable system architecture as well as high [[fault-tolerance]] capability. Moreover, because each droplet can be controlled independently, these systems also have dynamic reconfigurability, whereby groups of unit cells in a microfluidic array can be reconfigured to change their functionality during the concurrent execution of a set of bioassays. Although droplets are manipulated in confined microfluidic channels, since the control on droplets is not independent, it should not be confused as \"digital microfluidics\". One common actuation method for digital microfluidics is [[electrowetting]]-on-dielectric ([[EWOD]])<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Junghoon Lee|last2=Chang-Jin Kim|date=2000-06|title=Surface-tension-driven microactuation based on continuous electrowetting|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/846697/|journal=Journal of Microelectromechanical Systems|volume=9|issue=2|pages=171\u2013180|doi=10.1109/84.846697|issn=1057-7157}}</ref>. Many lab-on-a-chip applications have been demonstrated within the digital microfluidics paradigm using electrowetting. However, recently other techniques for droplet manipulation have also been demonstrated using magnetic force,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Zhang | first1 = Yi | last2 = Nguyen | first2 = Nam-Trung | year = 2017 | title = Magnetic digital microfluidics\u2013a review | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5d0baf973be5fb8971880ff9fc39069fd0d80297| journal = Lab on a Chip | volume = 17 | issue = 6| pages = 994\u20131008 | doi=10.1039/c7lc00025a| pmid = 28220916 | hdl = 10072/344389 }}</ref> [[surface acoustic wave]]s, [[optoelectrowetting]], mechanical actuation,<ref name=\"microfluidics piezo\">{{Cite journal | doi=10.1007/s10544-010-9445-y| pmid=20559875| title=Advanced microfluidic droplet manipulation based on piezoelectric actuation| journal=Biomedical Microdevices| volume=12| issue=5| pages=907\u2013914| year=2010| last1=Shemesh| first1=Jonathan| last2=Bransky| first2=Avishay| last3=Khoury| first3=Maria| last4=Levenberg| first4=Shulamit}}</ref>  etc.\n\n=== Paper-based microfluidics ===\n{{Main|Paper-based microfluidics}}\nPaper-based microfluidic devices fill a growing niche for portable, cheap, and user-friendly medical diagnostic systems.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite book|title=Open Microfluidics|last=Berthier|first=Jean|last2=Brakke|first2=Kenneth A.|last3=Berthier|first3=Erwin|date=2016|publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc.|isbn=9781118720936|pages=229\u2013256|language=en|doi=10.1002/9781118720936.ch7}}</ref> \nPaper based microfluidics rely on the phenomenon of capillary penetration in porous media.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/j.jcis.2018.12.068|pmid=30594833|title=Tailoring porous media for controllable capillary flow|journal=Journal of Colloid and Interface Science|volume=539|pages=379\u2013387|year=2019|last1=Liu|first1=Mingchao|last2=Suo|first2=Si|last3=Wu|first3=Jian|last4=Gan|first4=Yixiang|last5=Ah Hanaor|first5=Dorian|last6=Chen|first6=C.Q.|bibcode=2019JCIS..539..379L}}</ref> To tune fluid penetration in porous substrates such as paper in two and three dimensions, the pore structure, wettability and geometry of the microfluidic devices can be controlled while the viscosity and evaporation rate of the liquid play a further significant role. Many such devices feature hydrophobic barriers on hydrophilic paper that passively transport aqueous solutions to outlets where biological reactions take place.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5YQlDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=Microfabrication+Techniques+for+Microfluidic+Devices+Silverio#v=onepage&q=Microfabrication%20Techniques%20for%20Microfluidic%20Devices%20Silverio&f=false|title=Complex Fluid-Flows in Microfluidics|last=Galindo-Rosales|first=Francisco Jos\u00e9|date=2017-05-26|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319595931|language=en}}</ref> Current applications include portable glucose detection<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite journal|last=Martinez|first=Andres W.|last2=Phillips|first2=Scott T.|last3=Butte|first3=Manish J.|last4=Whitesides|first4=George M.|date=2007|title=Patterned paper as a platform for inexpensive, low-volume, portable bioassays|journal= Angewandte Chemie International Edition|volume=46|issue=8|pages=1318\u20131320|doi=10.1002/anie.200603817|issn=1433-7851|pmc=3804133|pmid=17211899}}</ref> and environmental testing,<ref name=\":72\">{{Cite journal|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/271508549|title=Smartphone Detection of Escherichia coli From Field Water Samples on Paper Microfluidics|journal=IEEE Sensors Journal|last=Park|first=Tu San|last2=Yoon|first2=Jeong-Yeol|date=2015-03-01|volume=15|issue=3|pages=1902|bibcode=2015ISenJ..15.1902P|doi=10.1109/JSEN.2014.2367039}}</ref> with hopes of reaching areas that lack advanced medical diagnostic tools.\n\n===DNA chips (microarrays)===\n\nEarly biochips were based on the idea of a [[DNA microarray]], e.g., the GeneChip DNAarray from [[Affymetrix]], which is a piece of glass, plastic or silicon substrate, on which pieces of DNA (probes) are affixed in a microscopic array. Similar to a [[DNA microarray]], a [[protein array]] is a miniature array where a multitude of different capture agents, most frequently monoclonal [[antibodies]], are deposited on a chip surface; they are used to determine the presence and/or amount of [[protein]]s in biological samples, e.g., [[blood]]. A drawback of [[DNA]] and [[protein array]]s is that they are neither reconfigurable nor [[scalable]] after manufacture. [[Digital microfluidics]] has been described as a means for carrying out [[Digital PCR]].\n\n===Molecular biology===\nIn addition to microarrays, biochips have been designed for two-dimensional [[electrophoresis]],<ref name= Fan>{{cite book |author= Fan|year=2009|chapter=Two-Dimensional Electrophoresis in a Chip|title=Lab-on-a-Chip Technology: Biomolecular Separation and Analysis|publisher=Caister Academic Press|isbn= 978-1-904455-47-9|display-authors=etal}}</ref> [[transcriptome]] analysis,<ref name= BontouxN>{{cite book |author= Bontoux|year=2009|chapter=Elaborating Lab-on-a-Chips for Single-cell Transcriptome Analysis|title=Lab-on-a-Chip Technology: Biomolecular Separation and Analysis|publisher=Caister Academic Press|isbn= 978-1-904455-47-9|display-authors=etal}}</ref> and [[PCR]] amplification.<ref name= Cadync>{{cite book |author= Cady, NC|year=2009|chapter=Microchip-based PCR Amplification Systems|title=Lab-on-a-Chip Technology: Biomolecular Separation and Analysis|publisher=Caister Academic Press|isbn= 978-1-904455-47-9}}</ref> Other applications include various electrophoresis and [[liquid chromatography]] applications for proteins and [[DNA]], cell separation, in particular, blood cell separation, protein analysis, cell manipulation and analysis including cell viability analysis <ref name=\"pubs.rsc.org\"/> and [[microorganism]] capturing.<ref name=\"Herold2\"/>\n\n===Evolutionary biology===\n\nBy combining microfluidics with [[landscape ecology]] and [[nanofluidics]], a nano/micro fabricated fluidic landscape can be constructed by building local patches of [[bacterial]] [[habitat]] and connecting them by dispersal corridors. The resulting landscapes can be used as physical implementations of an [[adaptive landscape]],<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Keymer J.E. |author2=P. Galajda |author3=C. Muldoon R. |author4=R. Austin  |last-author-amp=yes |date=November 2006 |title=Bacterial metapopulations in nanofabricated landscapes|journal= Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=103 |issue=46 |pages= 17290\u2013295 |pmc= 1635019|doi=10.1073/pnas.0607971103  |bibcode = 2006PNAS..10317290K |pmid=17090676}}</ref>  by generating a spatial mosaic of patches of opportunity distributed in space and time. The patchy nature of these fluidic landscapes allows for the study of adapting bacterial cells in a [[metapopulation]] system. The [[evolutionary ecology]] of these bacterial systems in these synthetic ecosystems allows for using [[biophysics]] to address questions in [[evolutionary biology]].\n\n===Cell behavior===\n{{Main|Microfluidic cell culture}}\nThe ability to create precise and carefully controlled [[chemoattractant]] gradients makes microfluidics the ideal tool to study motility <ref>{{cite journal |author1=Axel Hochstetter |author2=Eric Stellamanns |author3= Siddharth Deshpande |author4=Sravanti Uppaluri |author5= Markus Engstler |author6=Thomas Pfohl |title=Microfluidics-based single cell analysis reveals drug-dependent motility changes in trypanosomes  |journal= Lab Chip |volume=15 |issue= 8|pages= 1961\u20131968 |year=2015 |pmid=25756872 |doi=  10.1039/C5LC00124B|url=https://edoc.unibas.ch/41485/1/C5LC00124B.pdf }}</ref>, [[chemotaxis]] and the ability to evolve / develop resistance to antibiotics in small populations of microorganisms and in a short period of time. These microorganisms including [[bacteria]] <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Ahmed | first1 = T. | last2 = Shimizu | first2 = T.S. | last3 = Stocker | first3 = R. | year = 2010 | title = Microfluidics for bacterial chemotaxis | url = http://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlelanding/2010/ib/c0ib00049c | journal = Integrative Biology | volume = 2 | issue = 11\u201312| pages = 604\u2013629 | doi = 10.1039/C0IB00049C | pmid = 20967322 | hdl = 1721.1/66851 }}</ref> and the broad range of organisms that form the marine [[microbial loop]],<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Seymour | first1 = J.R. | last2 = Simo' | first2 = R. | last3 = Ahmed | first3 = T. | last4 = Stocker | first4 = R. | year = 2010 | title = Chemoattraction to dimethylsulfoniopropionate throughout the marine microbial food web | journal = Science | volume = 329 | issue = 5989| pages = 342\u2013345 | doi = 10.1126/science.1188418 |bibcode = 2010Sci...329..342S | pmid=20647471| url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/93b2ab42cfabf3cb5982648fd7ffa55d850655c8 }}</ref> responsible for regulating much of the oceans' biogeochemistry.\n\nMicrofluidics has also greatly aided the study of [[durotaxis]] by facilitating the creation of durotactic (stiffness) gradients.\n\n===Cellular biophysics===\n\nBy rectifying the motion of individual swimming bacteria,<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Galajda P |author2=J.E. Keymer |author3=P Chaikin |author4=R. Austin |date=December 2007 |title=A Wall of Funnels Concentrates Swimming Bacteria|journal= Journal of Bacteriology |volume=189 |issue=23 |pages= 8704\u20138707 |pmc= 2168927|doi=10.1128/JB.01033-07 |pmid=17890308}}</ref>  microfluidic structures can be used to extract mechanical motion from a population of motile bacterial cells.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Angelani L. |author2=R. Di Leonardo |author3=G. Ruocco |year=2009 |title=Self-Starting Micromotors in a Bacterial Bath|journal= Phys. Rev. Lett. |volume=102 |issue= 4|page= 048104 |pmc= |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.102.048104 |pmid=19257480 |bibcode=2009PhRvL.102d8104A|arxiv = 0812.2375 }}</ref>  This way, bacteria-powered rotors can be built.<ref>{{cite journal | title = A bacterial ratchet motor | first1 = R. | last1 = Di Leonardo | first2 = L. | last2 = Angelani | first3 = G. | last3 = Ruocco | first4 = V. | last4 = Iebba | first5 = M.P. | last5 = Conte | first6 = S. | last6 = Schippa | first7 = F. | last7 = De Angelis | first8 = F. | last8 = Mecarini | first9 = E. | last9 = Di Fabrizio  | journal =PNAS | volume = 107 | issue = 21 | pages = 9541\u20139545 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0910426107| pmid = 20457936 |arxiv = 0910.2899 |bibcode = 2010PNAS..107.9541D | pmc = 2906854 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Sokolova A. |author2=M.M. Apodacac |author3=B.A. Grzybowskic |author4=I.S. Aransona |date=December 2009 |title=Swimming bacteria power microscopic gears |journal= PNAS |volume=107 |issue=3 |pages=969\u2013974 |pmc= 2824308|doi=10.1073/pnas.0913015107|bibcode = 2010PNAS..107..969S |pmid=20080560}}</ref>\n\n===Optics===\nThe merger of microfluidics and optics is typical known as [[optofluidics]]. Examples of optofluidic devices are tunable microlens arrays<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1364/OE.16.008084|pmid = 18545521|title = Liquid micro-lens array activated by selective electrowetting on lithium niobate substrates|journal = Optics Express|volume = 16|issue = 11|pages = 8084\u201393|year = 2008|last1 = Grilli|first1 = S.|last2 = Miccio|first2 = L.|last3 = Vespini|first3 = V.|last4 = Finizio|first4 = A.|last5 = De Nicola|first5 = S.|last6 = Ferraro|first6 = Pietro|bibcode = 2008OExpr..16.8084G|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/e94312047e327ae6017e94e1a1bfd7c1f6d918a0}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1364/OPN.19.12.000034|title = Manipulating Thin Liquid Films for Tunable Microlens Arrays|journal = Optics and Photonics News|volume = 19|issue = 12|pages = 34|year = 2008|last1 = Ferraro|first1 = Pietro|last2 = Miccio|first2 = Lisa|last3 = Grilli|first3 = Simonetta|last4 = Finizio|first4 = Andrea|last5 = De Nicola|first5 = Sergio|last6 = Vespini|first6 = Veronica}}</ref> and optofluidic microscopes.\n\nMicrofluidic flow enables fast sample throughput, automated imaging of large sample populations, as well as 3D capabilities.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1039/C4LC00701H|pmid = 25256716|pmc = 5859944|title = Flow-scanning optical tomography|journal = Lab Chip|volume = 14|issue = 23|pages = 4447\u20134450|year = 2014|last1 = P\u00e9gard|first1 = Nicolas C.|last2 = Toth|first2 = Marton L.|last3 = Driscoll|first3 = Monica|last4 = Fleischer|first4 = Jason W.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |doi = 10.1364/BIOMED.2012.BM4B.4|chapter = 3D microfluidic microscopy using a tilted channel|title = Biomedical Optics and 3-D Imaging|pages = BM4B.4|year = 2012|last1 = P\u00e9gard|first1 = Nicolas C.|last2 = Fleischer|first2 = Jason W.|isbn = 978-1-55752-942-8}}</ref> or superresolution.<ref>http://link.aip.org/link/?APPLAB/102/161115/1</ref>\n\n===Acoustic droplet ejection (ADE)===\n\n[[Acoustic droplet ejection]] uses a pulse of [[ultrasound]] to move low volumes of [[fluids]] (typically nanoliters or picoliters) without any physical contact. This technology focuses acoustic energy into a fluid sample to eject droplets as small as a millionth of a millionth of a litre (picoliter = 10<sup>\u221212</sup> litre). ADE technology is a very gentle process, and it can be used to transfer proteins, high molecular weight DNA and live cells without damage or loss of viability. This feature makes the technology suitable for a wide variety of applications including [[proteomics]] and cell-based assays.\n\n===Fuel cells===\n{{Details|Electroosmotic pump}}\nMicrofluidic [[fuel cells]] can use laminar flow to separate the fuel and its oxidant to control the interaction of the two fluids without the physical barrier that conventional fuel cells require.<ref>[http://microfluidics.stanford.edu/fuel_cells.htm Water Management in PEM Fuel Cells]   {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080628192632/http://microfluidics.stanford.edu/fuel_cells.htm |date=June 28, 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.aps.org/publications/apsnews/200505/fuel.cfm Building a Better Fuel Cell Using Microfluidics]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080305215325/http://www.me.mtu.edu/mnit/ Fuel Cell Initiative at MnIT Microfluidics Laboratory]</ref>\n\n=== Astrobiology ===\nTo understand the prospects for life to exist elsewhere in the universe, [[Astrobiology|astrobiologists]] are interested in measuring the chemical composition of extraplanetary bodies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nai.nasa.gov/media/medialibrary/2015/10/NASA_Astrobiology_Strategy_2015_151008.pdf|title=NASA Astrobiology Strategy, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222190306/https://nai.nasa.gov/media/medialibrary/2015/10/NASA_Astrobiology_Strategy_2015_151008.pdf|archive-date=2016-12-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> Because of their small size and wide-ranging functionality, microfluidic devices are uniquely suited for these remote sample analyses.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beebe|first=David J.|last2=Mensing|first2=Glennys A.|last3=Walker|first3=Glenn M.|date=2002|title=Physics and applications of microfluidics in biology|journal=Annual Review of Biomedical Engineering|volume=4|pages=261\u2013286|doi=10.1146/annurev.bioeng.4.112601.125916|issn=1523-9829|pmid=12117759}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Theberge|first=Ashleigh B.|last2=Courtois|first2=Fabienne|last3=Schaerli|first3=Yolanda|last4=Fischlechner|first4=Martin|last5=Abell|first5=Chris|last6=Hollfelder|first6=Florian|last7=Huck|first7=Wilhelm T. S.|date=2010-08-09|title=Microdroplets in microfluidics: an evolving platform for discoveries in chemistry and biology|url=https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/340192/2/__soton.ac.uk_ude_personalfiles_users_jks1m11_mydesktop_theberge_2010_microdroplets%2520in%2520microfluidics-an%2520evolving%2520platform%2520for%2520discoveries%2520in%2520chemistry%2520and%2520biology.pdf|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|volume=49|issue=34|pages=5846\u20135868|doi=10.1002/anie.200906653|issn=1521-3773|pmid=20572214}}<!--https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/340192/2/__soton.ac.uk_ude_personalfiles_users_jks1m11_mydesktop_theberge_2010_microdroplets%2520in%2520microfluidics-an%2520evolving%2520platform%2520for%2520discoveries%2520in%2520chemistry%2520and%2520biology.pdf--></ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=van Dinther|first=A. M. C.|last2=Schro\u00ebn|first2=C. G. P. H.|last3=Vergeldt|first3=F. J.|last4=van der Sman|first4=R. G. M.|last5=Boom|first5=R. M.|date=2012-05-15|title=Suspension flow in microfluidic devices--a review of experimental techniques focussing on concentration and velocity gradients|journal=Advances in Colloid and Interface Science|volume=173|pages=23\u201334|doi=10.1016/j.cis.2012.02.003|issn=1873-3727|pmid=22405541}}</ref>  From an extraterrestrial sample, the organic content can be assessed using microchip [[capillary electrophoresis]] and selective fluorescent dyes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mora|first=Maria F.|last2=Greer|first2=Frank|last3=Stockton|first3=Amanda M.|last4=Bryant|first4=Sherrisse|last5=Willis|first5=Peter A.|date=2011-11-15|title=Toward Total Automation of Microfluidics for Extraterrestial [sic] In Situ Analysis|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=83|issue=22|pages=8636\u20138641|doi=10.1021/ac202095k|pmid=21972965|issn=0003-2700}}</ref>  These devices are capable of detecting [[amino acid]]s,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chiesl|first=Thomas N.|last2=Chu|first2=Wai K.|last3=Stockton|first3=Amanda M.|last4=Amashukeli|first4=Xenia|last5=Grunthaner|first5=Frank|last6=Mathies|first6=Richard A.|date=2009-04-01|title=Enhanced Amine and Amino Acid Analysis Using Pacific Blue and the Mars Organic Analyzer Microchip Capillary Electrophoresis System|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=81|issue=7|pages=2537\u20132544|doi=10.1021/ac8023334|pmid=19245228|issn=0003-2700}}</ref> [[peptide]]s,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kaiser|first=R. I.|last2=Stockton|first2=A. M.|last3=Kim|first3=Y. S.|last4=Jensen|first4=E. C.|last5=Mathies|first5=R. A.|date=2013|title=On the Formation of Dipeptides in Interstellar Model Ices|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|language=en|volume=765|issue=2|pages=111|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/765/2/111|issn=0004-637X|bibcode=2013ApJ...765..111K}}</ref> [[fatty acid]]s,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stockton|first=Amanda M.|last2=Tjin|first2=Caroline Chandra|last3=Chiesl|first3=Thomas N.|last4=Mathies|first4=Richard A.|date=July 2011|title=Analysis of carbonaceous biomarkers with the Mars Organic Analyzer microchip capillary electrophoresis system: carboxylic acids|journal=Astrobiology|volume=11|issue=6|pages=519\u2013528|doi=10.1089/ast.2011.0634|issn=1557-8070|pmid=21790324|bibcode=2011AsBio..11..519S}}</ref> and simple [[aldehyde]]s, [[ketone]]s,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stockton|first=Amanda M.|last2=Tjin|first2=Caroline Chandra|last3=Huang|first3=Grace L.|last4=Benhabib|first4=Merwan|last5=Chiesl|first5=Thomas N.|last6=Mathies|first6=Richard A.|date=2010-11-01|title=Analysis of carbonaceous biomarkers with the Mars Organic Analyzer microchip capillary electrophoresis system: Aldehydes and ketones|journal=Electrophoresis|language=en|volume=31|issue=22|pages=3642\u20133649|doi=10.1002/elps.201000424|pmid=20967779|issn=1522-2683}}</ref> and [[thiol]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Microchip Capillary Electrophoresis Protocols|volume=1274|last=Mora|first=Maria F.|last2=Stockton|first2=Amanda M.|last3=Willis|first3=Peter A.|date=2015|publisher=Humana Press, New York, NY|isbn=9781493923526|series=Methods in Molecular Biology|pages=43\u201352|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-1-4939-2353-3_4|pmid = 25673481}}</ref> These analyses coupled together could allow powerful detection of the key components of life, and hopefully inform our search for functioning extraterrestrial life.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bowden|first=Stephen A.|last2=Wilson|first2=Rab|last3=Taylor|first3=Colin|last4=Cooper|first4=Jonathan M.|last5=Parnell|first5=John|date=January 2007|title=The extraction of intracrystalline biomarkers and other organic compounds from sulphate minerals using a microfluidic format \u2013 a feasibility study for remote fossil-life detection using a microfluidic H-cell|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/international-journal-of-astrobiology/article/the-extraction-of-intracrystalline-biomarkers-and-other-organic-compounds-from-sulphate-minerals-using-a-microfluidic-format-a-feasibility-study-for-remote-fossil-life-detection-using-a-microfluidic-h-cell/C66EB723687CB09F2DAB638A074CBA9D|journal=International Journal of Astrobiology|language=en|volume=6|issue=1|pages=27\u201336|doi=10.1017/S147355040600351X|issn=1475-3006|bibcode=2007IJAsB...6...27B}}</ref>\n\n===Future directions===\n* Microfluidic drug assays:<ref name=\"Microfluidic Devices for Drug Assays\">{{cite journal | last1 = Regnault | first1 = Cl\u00e9ment | last2 = Dheeman | first2 = Dharmendra S. | last3 = Hochstetter | first3 = Axel | year = 2018 | title = Microfluidic Devices for Drug Assays | journal = High Throughput | volume = 7 | issue = 2| pages = 18 | doi =10.3390/ht7020018 | pmid = 29925804 | pmc = 6023517 }}</ref>\n* On-chip characterization:<ref name=\"Development and applications of a microfluidic reactor with multiple analytical probes\">{{cite journal | last1 = Jesse | last2 = Debono | first2 = Michael | last3 = Kwan | first3 = Chi-Hang | last4 = Abolhasani | first4 = Milad | last5 = Guenther | first5 = Axel | last6 = Kumacheva | first6 = Eugenia | year = 2012 | title = Development and applications of a microfluidic reactor with multiple analytical probes | journal = Analyst | volume = 137 | issue = 2| pages = 444\u2013450 | doi = 10.1039/C1AN15940B | pmid = 22108956 | bibcode = 2012Ana...137..444G | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/576657418ca0d6f3128c1f3f2a21ca0bad49bcb4 }}</ref>\n* Microfluidics in the classroom: On-chip acid-base titrations<ref name=\"Education: a microfluidic platform for university-level analytical chemistry laboratories\">{{cite journal | last1 = Greener | first1 = Jesse | last2 = Tumarkin | first2 = Ethan | last3 = Debono | first3 = Michael | last4 = Kumacheva | first4 = Eugenia | year = 2012 | title = Education: a microfluidic platform for university-level analytical chemistry laboratories | journal = Lab Chip | volume = 12 | issue = 4| pages = 696\u2013701 | doi = 10.1039/C2LC20951A | pmid = 22237720 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/cb0a5fd683ea67e8b655b0fe3b06ecaef1b3a50c }}</ref>\n* [[Sepsis]] detection [https://medicalxpress.com/news/2019-07-microfluidics-device-sepsis-minutes.html in minutes not days].\n* Unlocking multi-angle imaging for microfluidic devices <ref name=\"Presegmentation Procedure Generates Smooth-Sided Microfluidic Devices: Unlocking Multiangle Imaging for Everyone?\">{{cite journal|author1=Axel Hochstetter |date=December 2019 |title=Presegmentation Procedure Generates Smooth-Sided Microfluidic Devices: Unlocking Multiangle Imaging for Everyone?|journal= ACS Omega |volume=4 |issue=25 |pages=20972\u201320977 |doi=10.1021/acsomega.9b02139|pmid=31867488 |pmc=6921255 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biology|Technology}}\n* [[Adva